@Node Intro "What's is SPlayer ?"

SPlayer is a GUI for Play16 and Mpega and can Play Audio CD's on SCSI/ATAPI
CD Roms.

SPlayer controls most of Play16's and Mpega's functions. Does wonders for
Audio CDs too. Easy to use use and almost every feature can be configured
to your individual taste.


Features: (to name a few)
---------

- Play16/Mpega/CD GUI, All in one.

- Mpeg Tag Editor

- Elapsed time Slider

- Each GUI has it's own prefs.

- Can select track via keyboard, playlist, or requester.

- Menus for added simplicity.

- SPlayer can be shrunk, expanded, and iconified.

- Play16/Mpega play lists can be saved.

- Audio CD Title and track names can be edited. Saves on the fly as you
  type.

- Any 8 Point font can be used by using the Font requester.

- Low CPU and memory usage.

- And much, much more


SPlayer is MAIL-WARE

I have spent many hours on SPlayer. Years to be exact. If you use this
program let me know. You can @{" E-Mail me or send a Post card " Link Author}. The future
of SPlayer relies on this. Since SPlayer is free, I don't think it's much
to ask for a little feedback. Please no MUI vs GadTools Flame wars.


@Endnode

@Node Install "How to install SPlayer"

Just click on the install Icon..that's it.

You can put SPlayer where ever you want.

  <<<< YOU MUST RUN THE INSTALLER >>>>

Failure to do this will cause certain doom....

ie: The program will not run as intended.

Manual installation is possible.

If you want to see where the Installer puts everything, click @{" here " Link Bugs}

@EndNode

@Node Req "Requirements to run SPlayer."

- An Amiga

- OS 3.0 or greater

- 68000 for Play16, 68020 or greater for Mpega

- 512K minimum of memeory.

- Play16 1.9 (from Aminet)

- Mpega 3.5 (from Aminet)

- mpega.library archive (from Aminet)

- AHI v4.x (from Aminet). This optional but comes in handy.

For Play16 an '020 or higher is recommended for playing 16-Bit samples
at 14-Bit resolution.

Mpega needs a lot of CPU power. An 030/50 is usually the bare minimum
for Mp2 playback. 040 or 060 recommended

Read the Play16 and Mpega docs for more info.

@EndNode

@Node Guis "SPlayer Controls and the Play16/Mpega/CD  GUIs"

@{JCenter}@{"Main Controls" SYSTEM "Sys:Utilities/MultiView GuidePics/SMain.pic"}

@{JCenter}@{"Displays" SYSTEM "Sys:Utilities/MultiView GuidePics/SDisplay.pic"}

@{JCenter}@{" Play16 GUI " SYSTEM "Sys:Utilities/MultiView GuidePics/SPlay16.pic"}

@{JCenter}@{"Mpega GUI" SYSTEM "Sys:Utilities/MultiView GuidePics/SMpega.pic"}

@{JCenter}@{"CD Player GUI" SYSTEM "Sys:Utilities/MultiView GuidePics/SCD.pic"}

@{JCenter}@{"SPlayer Small GUI" SYSTEM "Sys:Utilities/MultiView GuidePics/SGui.pic"}

@{JLeft}
Special modes:

Play Mode: ("Single" must be selected)
---------

When you press Play SPlayer goes into Play Mode. The Display will show ">"
and when the sample is finished the Display will show ">|" By pressing Skip
forward or Skip back the sample will play automatically. You do have to
press Play again.

Pressing Stop at any time will exit Play Mode. The Display will change
to the Stopped Symbol. This comes in handy when you do not want the next
sample to play immediately.

* Hitting Stop twice in a row will reset the playing list back to Track 1.

Scan:
-----

In Scan Mode (Mpega and CD only) the scanning speed will slow down when
there is 10 seconds left of the Mpeg/CD track. This wil give you time to go
back into the sample without having SPlayer skip to the next one.

Save Mode:
----------

All the files you save out will be in their native format. Voc, wav, aiff,
etc. They will not be converted. Since Play16 can play these files, I see no
need to have SPlayer convert them.

NOTE: SPlayer will try to switch GUIs when an Mpeg is loaded on the Play16
side or vice-versa. Please make sure all you Mpegs are labeled with .mp1,
.mp2, or .mp3 at the end of the Mpeg file's name. SPlayer uses these
extensions to prevent the wrong GUI from Playing them if you accidently
loaded the wrong sample type.

Play16 Raw modes:
-----------------

Auto  : This mode will try to play all audio formats. The 8/16 and Mono/Stereo
        gadgets are ghosted in this mode.

Strict: This mode will only play valid sound files. Aiff, Wav, 8svx, etc.

Raw   : If you enter a frequency in Hz in the auto gadget, Play16 will enter raw
        mode. The 8/16 Bit and Mono/Stereo gadgets will now be available.
        Read the Play16 docs on how to use these features.


**** NOTE *********************************************************************
*                                                                             *
* These settings are remembered while SPlayer is running. They are not saved. *
*                                                                             *
*******************************************************************************


Numeric Keypad Track Entry:
---------------------------

Entering a 2 digit number, for example "01" would play track one. If you
enter a wrong digit, any non-numeric number key will cancel the entry. You
can now re-enter the track number. Using the CX_PLAY keys when the SPlayer
window is not active (you are doing other things in other windows or
screens), lets you select a track from there. SPlayer will wait for 2
numbers to be entered either bt the numeric key pad or the usual keys. Same
rules apply here as stated above

@EndNode

