         and off. Useful for "Dirty" sounding samples.
      -  Slight GUI change to make room for the above mentioned options.
      -  Included RequestFile 34.7 by Simon Dick. Now  will
         run on 2.x machines.

v1.0  -  First Public Release of SPlayer.

v.9   -  Fixed bug #2008. Raid finally did the trick..Got ya !

v.8   -  Stop actually works now...

v.5   -  Too strange to mention. Fixed it though.

v.1   -  First Semi-Usable version of SPlayer.

V.0   -  Didn't exist yet.

@EndNode

@Node IBrowse "IBrowse Set-Up"

SPlayer can now be called up by IBrowse to play sound files off of
the net. The only exception is if you use IBrowse on FTP sites. IBrowse
uses a different protocol for those pages.

How to Set up the IBrowse Preferences to use SPlayer:

1) Go into "Preferences" in IBrowse

2) Select "General"

3) In the window that pops up click on "Ext.viewer"

4) Select "Add"

5) In "Mime Type" enter "Audio". Press return

6) Enter "*" in the adjacent box. (to the right). Press enter

7) In "Extension" type "wav,voc,aiff,au,maud,iff" pres enter

8) Beside "Action" select the "Ext.viewer" button

9) In the "Viewer" box, type or use the file gadget, enter the path and
   name os SPlayer.

10) In "Arguments" enter %f and press return.

11) Click on "OK"

12) In the "Preferences" menu again, select "Save Settings"

That's it. Now whenever you click on a wav, aiff,au,etc. file, SPlayer will
pop up and play the sample.

@EndNode

@Node AWeb_2.0 "AWeb 1.x to 2.0 Set-Up"

SPlayer can now be called up by AWeb to play sound files off of the net.

How to Set up the AWeb Preferences to use SPlayer:

1) Select "Change Settings" from the "Settings" menu

2) Use the page cycle gadget and keep clicking on it till you reach the
   Mime Type and External Viewer Page

3) Click on ADD

4) Type "AUDIO" in the Type box (left side) and "*" in the box beside it.

5) In "Extensions" enter "wav aiff voc iff maud". Press return

6) In "Command" enter the path of SPlayer including it's name.

7) In "Arguments" enter %s and press return.

8) Click on "Save"

That's it. Now whenever you click on a wav, aiff,au,etc. file, SPlayer will
pop up and play the sample.

@EndNode

@Node AWeb_2.1 "AWeb 2.1 Set-Up"

SPlayer can now be called up by AWeb to play sound files off of the net.

How to set up the AWeb Preferences to use SPlayer:

1) Select "Browser Settings" from the "Settings" menu

2) Select Viewers (5) from that window

3) Click on ADD

4) Type "AUDIO" in the Type box (left side) and "*" in the box beside it.

5) In "Extensions" enter "wav aiff voc iff maud". Press return

6) In "Command" enter the path of SPlayer including it's name.

7) In "Arguments" enter %s and press return.

8) Click on "Save"

That's it. Now whenever you click on a wav, aiff,au,etc. file, SPlayer will
pop up and play the sample.

@EndNode

@Node Tool "Menus and Tooltypes"

SPlayer 1.9e has a menu that sets and saves almost all tooltypes. The
Tooltypes listed below can now be used for reference only. Cool, eh ?
No more mucking around with SPlayers .info file :)

The only tooltpes you have to edit is CX_HIDE, CX_SHOW, and CX_Play. These
set what key combo shows or hides SPlayer's GUI.

Defaults are : CX_SHOW=ctrl lalt s
               CX_HIDE=ctrl lalt h
               CX_PLAY=ctrl lalt f10

Chnage these to whatever you like.


What's in the Menu

SPlayer
-------

Iconify      : Gets SPlayer's GUI out of your face. Double click on the
               Appicon or use the CX_SHOW keys to un-iconify it.

About:       : Brings up a window that shows some really neat Stuff


Quit         : Hmmm....wonder what this does ?


Settings
--------

AutoPlay     : This will automatically play samples after they are loaded
               via the requester or Reload Gadget.

AutoLoad     : If you have saved a sample list that list will be loaded
               automatically on startup.

WaitBuffer   : Delays playing of Mpegs untill the Audio Buffer is full.
               This is usefull for slow systems or hard drives.

Small GUI    : If on, SPlayer will use a smaller window. It can be toggled
               between the 2 sizes with this memu item or via the GUI
               itself.

Text Scroll  : Will allow scrolling of track names that are longer than the
               display area.

               Off : No Text Scroll

               All : Always scroll track names

               Auto: Only scroll is track name is lonmger than the display
                     area.

Iconify Type : Toolmenu or Icon iconification

               Icon: Iconify to Icon on WB screen

               Menu: Iconify to Toolmenu on WB Title bar

GUI          : Select the GUI you want. Save settings will save this as
               the default GUI on SPlayer startup.


Priority     : Sets the priority for Play16/Mpega to run at. -1, 0, or +1
               The prority is can be unique to each GUI. In other words,
               Play16 and Mpega can have different priorities.

Font         : Brings up a Font requester. Pick any 8 point font. Only 8
               point fonts will show a number in the right side of the
               the requester.

CD Disc Path : With the requester, choose the path you want the CD ID files
               stored.

Save
Settings     : Saves the current menu options as tooltypes. All menu prefs
               are saved in SPlayers Icon. Current loaded sample paths and
               CD ID Disc paths are saved aswell. No need to edit them
               manually anymore (minus the CD GUI tooltypes).
               Use the GUI Prefs ("?" on the main GUI) to save all GUI
               gadgets and settings.


Project:
_______



Tag Editor   :  Bring up Mpeg Tag Editor (Mpega GUI)

Save To Disk :  In Play16 or Mpega mode, use this to save out the current
                sample that is showing on SPlayer's LCD display. The
                directory you save this sample in will become the default
                directory for future saves. This path also gets saved when
                "Save Settings" is used in the Settings menu.

Decode To Disk: In Mpega Mode you can save the mpeg as an Aiff or Wav file.
                Comes in handy for pre CD recording aswell as being able
                to play the decoded file using Play16. This is usefull for
                slower systems.



Tooltypes
---------

PLAY16DIR  : This is the Default Path were you keep your samples for
             Play16.

MPEGADIR   : This is the Default Path were you keep your samples for
             Mpega.

SAVEPATH   : The path where you want any of these samples to be saved

AUTOPLAY   : If you want the sample(s) to play after loading, set this
             to on by un-bracketing it.

AUTOLOAD   : This will cause the saved sample lists for the perspective
             GUI to be loaded automatically. Set this by un-bracketing it.

SMALLGUI   : 0 means the the Normal size GUI will be used. 1 sets it to
             small GUI mode. Save Settings will save this setting aswell

ITYPE      : 0=AppIcon.  1=AppMenu

GUI        : Switches to the selected GUI. Whatever GUI is loaded, will
             also be saved as the default GUI if you use "Save Settings".

PLAY16PRI  : Sets the priority that  will run at.
             -5 to +5 are reasonable numbers. 1 works well

MPEGAPRI   : Sets the priority that Mpega will run at.
             -5 to +5 are reasonable numbers. 1 works well

SCANSPEED  : This setting is for how fast you want to scan through
             Mpeg files in Mpega. 0 is fastest, 2 is slowest.

WAITBUFFER : 0=OFF, 1=ON. Tells Mpega to wait till the buffer is full
             before playing the Mpeg.

ITYPE      : Sets the Iconify mode fo SPlayer. 0=Icon, 1=Menu

CX_SHOW    : Uniconify or bring the GUI to front. "ctrl lalt s" is the
             default.

CX_HIDE    : Iconify the GUI. "ctrl lalt h" is the defualt.

CX_PLAY    : When the SPlayer window is iconified or not selected, using
             these hotkeys will let you enter the desired track number.

DISCPATH   : The path that the CD Id's are stored.

FONT       : The font that the SPlayer GUI will use.

SCROLL     : The value for Text Scroll. 0=off, 1=All, 2=Auto


NOTE: As long as the .info file (icon) is with SPlayer. These settings
are loaded from the Cli as well

@Endnode

@Node CLI "CLI and Opus Use"


CLI Usage
---------

I only recommend SPlayer to be used with 1 to 10 parameters from CLI

ie: SPlayer sample.wav test.wav pig.wav ......help.wav

There is a bug in one of the Blitz Basic commands that causes a GURU
if the paramerers exceed 256 chracters.

Directory Opus
--------------

Make a button in Opus and enter the following command and settings:

Select Workbench mode, not AmigaDos

Enter "SPlayer {F}

Select Run Asyncronously

Save these settings

Refer to you Opus Manual for more info

Select the samples and press the SPlayer button.

You may notice only 9 or 10 samples will load. This is normal. Quitting
SPlayer will load the next set of Samples (if there are any).

@Endnode

@Node ReqChange

I strongly recommend ReqChange 3.x by Magnus Holmgren. It gives SPlayer
and your system requesters more power.

ReqChange will centre requesters, as well as give you the indispensible
"All" button. SPlayer loves this feature. One click and all your samples
are loaded. Many more features too. Get it!

ReqChange can be found on Aminet.

@Endnode

